04598nam a22005295i 9780226822570DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226822570  a(DE-B1597)633763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF851b.W255 2023 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a138223/eng/202205131 aWalker, Rachel E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeauty and the Brain :bThe Science of Human Nature in Early America /cRachel E. Walker. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b26 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1 FOUNDING FACES -- t2 A NEW SCIENCE OF MAN -- t3 CHARACTER DETECTIVES -- t4 THE MANLY BROW MOVEMENT -- t5 CRIMINAL MINDS -- t6 FACING RACE -- tCONCLUSION -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining the history of phrenology and physiognomy, Beauty and the Brain proposes a bold new way of understanding the connection between science, politics, and popular culture in early America. Between the 1770s and the 1860s, people all across the globe relied on physiognomy and phrenology to evaluate human worth. These once-popular but now discredited disciplines were based on a deceptively simple premise: that facial features or skull shape could reveal a person’s intelligence, character, and personality. In the United States, these were culturally ubiquitous sciences that both elite thinkers and ordinary people used to understand human nature. While the modern world dismisses phrenology and physiognomy as silly and debunked disciplines, Beauty and the Brain shows why they must be taken seriously: they were the intellectual tools that a diverse group of Americans used to debate questions of race, gender, and social justice. While prominent intellectuals and political thinkers invoked these sciences to justify hierarchy, marginalized people and progressive activists deployed them for their own political aims, creatively interpreting human minds and bodies as they fought for racial justice and gender equality. Ultimately, though, physiognomy and phrenology were as dangerous as they were popular. In addition to validating the idea that external beauty was a sign of internal worth, these disciplines often appealed to the very people who were damaged by their prejudicial doctrines. In taking physiognomy and phrenology seriously, Beauty and the Brain recovers a vibrant—if largely forgotten—cultural and intellectual universe, showing how popular sciences shaped some of the greatest political debates of the American past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPhrenologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPhrenologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhrenologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhysiognomyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPhysiognomyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPhysiognomyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aphrenology, physiognomy, science, pseudoscience, nonfiction, human nature, class, race, gender, politics, popular culture, facial features, skull shape, anatomy, intelligence, character, personality, social justice, hierarchy, marginalization, activism, beauty, worth, value, appearance, surface, equality, prejudice, discrimination, immigration, anti-semitism, slavery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822570/original  a978-3-11-076650-9